Data Partitioning
Used by the Machine Learning algorithm
to train the model
Needed to find the best values for the
hyperparameters of the ML Pipeline
Used for reporting, once we have the
best model we test its performance
on the test set and report the results
a.k.a. Holdout sets
They contain examples that the learning
algorithm is not allowed to see
To be effective, partitioning has to satisfy 4 conditions:
Condition 1: Split was applied to raw data
Once we have access to raw examples, and before everything else, do the split.
Condition 2: Data was randomized before the split
Randomly shuffle your examples first, then do the split
Condition 3: Validation and Test sets follow the same distribution
When you select the best values of hyperparameters using the validation set, you want that this selection
yealds a model that works well in production.
The examples in the test set are your best representatives of the production data
Hence, the need for the validation and test sets to follow the same distribution
Condition 4: Leakage during the split was avoided
Group Leakage may occur during partitioning
E.g., Imagine you have magnetic resonance images of the brains of multiple patients.
Each image is labeled with certain brain disease, and the same patient may be represented by several
images taken at different times.
If you apply the partitioning techniques discussed above (shuffle, then split), images of the same
patient might appear both in the training and holdout data.
The model might learn from the particularities of the patient rather than the disease!
Solution: Group Partitioning!
Keeping all patient examples together in one set, either training or holdout
